            ['country_id' => 1, 'name' => 'Okinawa', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Okinawa is a tropical paradise in Japan\'s southernmost prefecture, known for its beautiful beaches, crystal-clear waters, and unique Ryukyu culture. Unlike mainland Japan, Okinawa offers a laid-back island vibe with year-round warm weather. Visitors can enjoy world-class snorkeling and diving in the Kerama Islands, explore the UNESCO-listed Shurijo Castle, and experience the distinctive Okinawan cuisine, including goya champuru (bitter melon stir-fry) and Okinawan soba. The islands are also known for their longevity, with many centenarians attributed to the healthy local diet and lifestyle. Whale watching between January and March is another highlight.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545569341-9eb8b30979d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Italy (id: 2)
            ['country_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Rome', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Rome, the Eternal City, is an open-air museum where ancient history comes alive at every corner. From the iconic Colosseum and Roman Forum to the Pantheon and Trevi Fountain, the city showcases over 2,500 years of history. As the capital of Italy and the heart of the Roman Empire and Catholicism, Rome offers unparalleled cultural experiences. Visitors can explore Vatican City, home to St. Peter\'s Basilica and the Sistine Chapel with Michelangelo\'s masterpiece. The city\'s charming piazzas, winding cobblestone streets, and delicious Roman cuisine, including carbonara, cacio e pepe, and authentic gelato, make every moment memorable. Rome\'s energy, history, and beauty have inspired artists and travelers for centuries.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552832230-c0197dd311b5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Venice', 'trip_type' => 'romantic', 'description' => 'Venice is a magical city built on 118 islands connected by canals and bridges, offering one of the world\'s most romantic settings. The Grand Canal winds through the city, lined with magnificent palaces and churches. St. Mark\'s Square, with its basilica and campanile, is the city\'s heart. Visitors can glide along the canals in a traditional gondola, explore the charming streets of Dorsoduro and Cannaregio, and admire masterpieces of Venetian art. The city is famous for Carnival, Murano glass, and Burano\'s colorful houses. Venice faces challenges from rising sea levels and mass tourism, making a visit increasingly precious. The sinking city offers unforgettable experiences, from watching sunset over the Grand Canal to enjoying fresh seafood at a canal-side trattoria.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514890547357-a9ee288728e0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Amalfi Coast', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'The Amalfi Coast is a stunning stretch of coastline in southern Italy, known for its dramatic cliffs, colorful villages perched above the Mediterranean, and beautiful beaches. Towns like Positano, Amalfi, and Ravello offer breathtaking views, lemon groves, and charming streets. The coast is a UNESCO World Heritage site, famous for its Mediterranean scenery, terraced vineyards, and historic villas. Visitors can take boat trips to the island of Capri, hike the Path of the Gods (Sentiero degli Dei), and enjoy fresh seafood and limoncello, a local lemon liqueur. The Amalfi Coast represents the Italian dream of "la dolce vita" with its relaxed pace, stunning sunsets, and romantic atmosphere.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523699601010-2b956a86752c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Thailand (id: 3)
            ['country_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Bangkok', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Bangkok, Thailand\'s capital, is a dizzying metropolis of contrasts where ancient temples stand beside gleaming skyscrapers, and peaceful canals (khlongs) coexist with chaotic traffic. The city offers adventures at every turn, from exploring the magnificent Grand Palace and Wat Phra Kaew (Temple of the Emerald Buddha) to bargaining at the massive Chatuchak Weekend Market. Visitors can experience floating markets, enjoy world-famous street food, and discover the city\'s legendary nightlife. Bangkok is also known for its luxurious spas, rooftop bars with panoramic views, and cultural shows. Despite its chaos, the city has a charm that captivates visitors, earning it a reputation as one of the world\'s most visited cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Chiang Mai', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Chiang Mai, nestled in the mountains of northern Thailand, offers a more relaxed alternative to Bangkok with its rich history, beautiful temples, and stunning natural surroundings. The city was the capital of the Lanna Kingdom and retains much of its cultural heritage, with over 300 temples including the famous Wat Phra That Doi Suthep perched on a mountain overlooking the city. Chiang Mai is a gateway to jungle trekking, ethical elephant sanctuaries, and hill tribe villages. The city is also famous for its Sunday Night Market, traditional crafts, and Northern Thai cuisine, including khao soi (coconut curry noodle soup). The surrounding mountains offer zip-lining, white-water rafting, and visits to beautiful waterfalls.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528181304807-1f2e7c1425b7?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Phuket', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Phuket is Thailand\'s largest island and one of Asia\'s most famous beach destinations, offering something for every type of traveler. The island features beautiful beaches like Patong, Kata, and Karon, each with its own character from lively party scenes to family-friendly relaxation. Beyond the beaches, Phuket offers the Big Buddha statue, the historic Old Town with Sino-Portuguese architecture, and the spectacular Phang Nga Bay with its limestone karsts and sea caves. Visitors can take day trips to the Phi Phi Islands, James Bond Island, and Similan Islands for world-class snorkeling and diving. Phuket is also known for its vibrant nightlife, seafood restaurants, and luxury resorts. The island\'s combination of natural beauty and modern amenities makes it a perennial favorite.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // France (id: 4)
            ['country_id' => 4, 'name' => 'Paris', 'trip_type' => 'romantic', 'description' => 'Paris, the City of Light, is synonymous with romance, art, fashion, and gastronomy. The city\'s iconic landmarks include the Eiffel Tower, Notre-Dame Cathedral, Arc de Triomphe, and the Louvre Museum, home to the Mona Lisa. Paris is divided into 20 arrondissements, each with its own character, from the bohemian Montmartre to the chic Saint-Germain-des-Prés. Visitors can stroll along the Seine, picnic in the Luxembourg Gardens, explore the Latin Quarter, and shop on the Champs-Élysées. The city is famous for its cafes, brasseries, and patisseries, where one can enjoy croissants, macarons, and coffee while watching the world go by. Paris offers endless cultural experiences, from world-class theater and opera to intimate jazz clubs. The city\'s beauty, history, and romance have inspired countless artists, writers, and lovers for centuries.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1502602898657-3e91760cbb34?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 4, 'name' => 'French Riviera', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'The French Riviera, or Côte d\'Azur, is a glamorous stretch of Mediterranean coastline that has attracted the rich and famous for centuries. From Saint-Tropez to Menton, the region offers beautiful beaches, luxury yachts, and chic seaside resorts. Nice, the largest city, features the famous Promenade des Anglais, colorful old town (Vieux Nice), and vibrant markets. Cannes is known for its film festival and luxury hotels. Monaco, an independent city-state, offers the Monte Carlo Casino and the Formula 1 Grand Prix. Antibes and Villefranche-sur-Mer offer charming old ports and beaches. The hinterland, including Èze and Saint-Paul-de-Vence, offers medieval villages with stunning views. The French Riviera\'s mild climate, beautiful scenery, and glamorous reputation make it a dream destination for beach lovers and luxury travelers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505852903341-fc8d3db1047d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 4, 'name' => 'Bordeaux', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Bordeaux is the wine capital of the world, surrounded by over 7,000 wine-producing châteaux and vineyards in the Gironde region. The city itself is a UNESCO World Heritage site, featuring elegant 18th-century architecture, the stunning Place de la Bourse with its water mirror, and the modern Cité du Vin wine museum. Bordeaux has undergone significant revitalization, with a new tram system, pedestrianized streets, and a vibrant food scene. Visitors can explore the city\'s many wine bars and restaurants, take day trips to wine regions like Saint-Émilion, Médoc, and Sauternes, and learn about wine production at various châteaux. The surrounding region also offers beautiful countryside, historic villages, and the Arcachon Bay with Europe\'s highest sand dune, the Dune du Pilat. Bordeaux combines culture, gastronomy, and wine in a sophisticated package.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513026705753-bc3dca4d74b8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Australia (id: 5)
            ['country_id' => 5, 'name' => 'Sydney', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Sydney is Australia\'s largest and most iconic city, famous for its stunning harbor, beautiful beaches, and laid-back lifestyle. The Sydney Opera House and Sydney Harbour Bridge dominate the skyline, and visitors can climb the bridge for spectacular views. Bondi Beach offers world-famous surfing and coastal walks to Bronte and Coogee. The city has a vibrant food scene, with seafood at the Sydney Fish Market, dining in The Rocks historic district, and trendy cafes in Surry Hills and Newtown. The Royal Botanic Garden, Taronga Zoo, and ferry trips to Manly offer family-friendly activities. Sydney\'s mild climate, outdoor lifestyle, and natural beauty make it one of the world\'s most livable cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506973035872-a4ec16b8e8d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 5, 'name' => 'Great Barrier Reef', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'The Great Barrier Reef is the world\'s largest coral reef system, stretching over 2,300 kilometers along Queensland\'s coast. It is one of the seven natural wonders of the world and can be seen from space. The reef is home to thousands of species of marine life, including colorful fish, sea turtles, dolphins, sharks, and whales. The gateway cities of Cairns, Townsville, and Airlie Beach offer tours to the reef, including snorkeling, diving, and glass-bottom boat trips. The Whitsunday Islands, with their white silica sand beaches and turquoise waters, are a highlight. The reef is a UNESCO World Heritage site and is under threat from climate change, making a visit increasingly precious. The Great Barrier Reef offers an unforgettable underwater adventure.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582967788606-a171c1080cb0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 5, 'name' => 'Melbourne', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Melbourne is Australia\'s cultural capital, known for its arts, music, food, and coffee culture. The city consistently ranks as one of the world\'s most livable cities. Melbourne\'s laneways are famous for their street art, hidden bars, and boutique shops. The city hosts major events like the Australian Open tennis, Melbourne Cup horse race, and Formula 1 Grand Prix. The surrounding region offers the Great Ocean Road with the Twelve Apostles, the Yarra Valley wine region, and Phillip Island with its penguin parade. Melbourne\'s diverse population has created a world-class food scene, with everything from high-end restaurants to ethnic eateries. The city\'s trams, Victorian architecture, and vibrant neighborhoods make it a joy to explore.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514395462725-fb4566210144?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Brazil (id: 6)
            ['country_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Rio de Janeiro', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Rio de Janeiro is a city of spectacular beauty, nestled between lush green mountains and the Atlantic Ocean. Known as the "Marvelous City," Rio is famous for its iconic landmarks: Christ the Redeemer atop Corcovado Mountain, Sugarloaf Mountain with its cable car, and the beaches of Copacabana and Ipanema. The city pulses with samba music and is home to the world\'s biggest Carnival celebration. Visitors can hike through Tijuca Forest, one of the world\'s largest urban forests, and enjoy the vibrant nightlife of Lapa with its famous arches. Rio\'s friendly locals, or "Cariocas," embody the joyful spirit of Brazil. Despite its challenges, Rio\'s natural beauty and infectious energy captivate all who visit.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1483729558449-99ef09a8c325?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Amazon Rainforest', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'The Amazon Rainforest is the world\'s largest tropical rainforest, covering over 5.5 million square kilometers across nine countries, with the majority in Brazil. Known as the "lungs of the Earth," the Amazon produces 20% of the world\'s oxygen and is home to an incredible diversity of plant and animal life. Visitors can explore the Amazon from gateway cities like Manaus, with its famous Opera House, and Belém. Jungle lodges offer guided tours to see monkeys, sloths, caimans, pink river dolphins, and countless bird species. The Meeting of the Waters, where the dark Rio Negro and sandy-colored Amazon River flow side by side without mixing, is a natural phenomenon. The Amazon offers a once-in-a-lifetime adventure into the heart of nature.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Salvador', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Salvador, the capital of Bahia state, is the heart of Afro-Brazilian culture, known for its vibrant music, dance, cuisine, and religion. The city\'s historic center, Pelourinho, is a UNESCO World Heritage site with colorful colonial buildings, cobblestone streets, and baroque churches. Salvador is the birthplace of capoeira, a unique martial art disguised as dance, and candomblé, an Afro-Brazilian religion. The city celebrates one of Brazil\'s most authentic Carnivals, with street parties and trios elétricos (sound trucks). Bahian cuisine, including acarajé (black-eyed pea fritters) and moqueca (seafood stew), reflects African influences. The city\'s beautiful beaches, including Porto da Barra and Itapuã, offer relaxation. Salvador\'s unique culture and energy make it a fascinating destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // India (id: 7)
            ['country_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Jaipur', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan, is known as the Pink City for its distinctive terracotta-pink buildings. The city is a treasure trove of Rajput architecture, including the magnificent Amber Fort, City Palace, Hawa Mahal (Palace of Winds), and Jantar Mantar observatory. Jaipur is part of India\'s Golden Triangle tourist circuit, along with Delhi and Agra. The city is famous for its vibrant bazaars selling textiles, jewelry, and handicrafts. Visitors can experience traditional Rajasthani cuisine, cultural performances, and elephant rides at the fort. Jaipur also serves as a gateway to other Rajasthan destinations like Jodhpur, Udaipur, and Jaisalmer. The city\'s rich history, colorful culture, and warm hospitality make it a highlight of any Indian journey.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1537996194471-e657df975ab4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Goa', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Goa is India\'s smallest state but one of its most popular tourist destinations, famous for its beautiful beaches, Portuguese heritage, and vibrant nightlife. The state is divided into North Goa (known for parties and bustling beaches like Baga and Calangute) and South Goa (known for quieter, more upscale beaches like Palolem and Benaulim). Beyond the beaches, Goa offers Portuguese-era churches, including the Basilica of Bom Jesus (a UNESCO World Heritage site), spice plantations, wildlife sanctuaries, and the Dudhsagar Falls. Goan cuisine, with its blend of Indian and Portuguese influences, features seafood, vindaloo, and fenny (cashew liquor). The state\'s relaxed vibe, friendly people, and beautiful landscapes make it a favorite among domestic and international tourists.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512343879784-a960bf40e7f2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Manali', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Manali is a picturesque hill station in the Indian Himalayas, located in the state of Himachal Pradesh. Situated at an altitude of 2,050 meters, Manali is a gateway to adventure sports and outdoor activities, including trekking, mountaineering, river rafting, paragliding, and skiing at Solang Valley. The town is also known for its ancient temples, including Hadimba Temple, Manu Temple, and Vashisht Hot Springs. Manali serves as the starting point for the high-altitude road to Leh, one of the world\'s most scenic routes. The surrounding mountains, apple orchards, and pine forests create a stunning backdrop. Manali\'s cool climate, adventure opportunities, and natural beauty make it a popular destination for both domestic and international travelers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501786223405-6d024d7c3b8d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Canada (id: 8)
            ['country_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Banff', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Banff is a resort town in the heart of the Canadian Rockies, located within Banff National Park, Canada\'s first national park and a UNESCO World Heritage site. The town is surrounded by stunning mountain scenery, including turquoise lakes like Lake Louise and Moraine Lake, glaciers, and abundant wildlife. Visitors can hike, ski at three world-class resorts (Mount Norquay, Sunshine Village, and Lake Louise), golf, or simply enjoy the views from the Banff Gondola. The town itself offers charming shops, restaurants, and hot springs. The Icefields Parkway, one of the world\'s most scenic drives, connects Banff to Jasper National Park. Banff\'s combination of natural beauty, outdoor activities, and mountain town charm makes it one of Canada\'s most popular destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503614472-8c93d56e92ce?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Vancouver', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Vancouver is a coastal city surrounded by mountains and ocean, offering year-round outdoor adventures. Stanley Park, one of North America\'s largest urban parks, features a scenic seawall, beaches, and the Vancouver Aquarium. The city hosted the 2010 Winter Olympics and offers skiing, snowboarding, and snowshoeing at Grouse Mountain, Cypress Mountain, and Mount Seymour, all within 30 minutes of downtown. Granville Island is a vibrant public market with food, art, and entertainment. Vancouver\'s diverse population has created a world-class food scene, particularly Asian cuisine. The city\'s mild climate, natural beauty, and outdoor lifestyle make it one of the world\'s most livable cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501594907352-04cda38ebc29?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Quebec City', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Quebec City is the capital of the province of Quebec and one of North America\'s oldest and most beautiful cities. Its historic district, Vieux-Québec (Old Quebec), is a UNESCO World Heritage site, featuring cobblestone streets, stone buildings, and the iconic Château Frontenac hotel. The city is surrounded by fortified walls, making it the only remaining walled city in North America north of Mexico. Quebec City is known for its French-Canadian culture, with French as the primary language, European-style cafes, and delicious cuisine, including poutine and tourtière. The city hosts the Winter Carnival, one of the world\'s largest winter festivals. Quebec City\'s romantic atmosphere, historic charm, and European feel make it a unique North American destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506619216599-9d16d0903dfd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Morocco (id: 9)
            ['country_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Marrakech', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Marrakech is a vibrant city that captures the essence of Morocco with its bustling souks, palaces, and gardens. The city\'s medina is a UNESCO World Heritage site, centered around Jemaa el-Fnaa square, which comes alive at night with storytellers, musicians, and food stalls. Key attractions include the Koutoubia Mosque, Bahia Palace, Saadian Tombs, and the Majorelle Garden (once owned by Yves Saint Laurent). The city is divided into the historic medina and the modern Gueliz district. Marrakech is known for its traditional riads (courtyard houses converted into guesthouses), hammams (public baths), and Moroccan cuisine, including tagines, couscous, and mint tea. The city serves as a gateway to the Atlas Mountains and Sahara Desert. Marrakech\'s exotic atmosphere, rich history, and vibrant culture make it one of Morocco\'s most popular destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1489749798305-4fea3ae63d43?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Sahara Desert', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'The Sahara Desert is the world\'s largest hot desert, covering much of North Africa. In Morocco, visitors can experience the Sahara through the Erg Chebbi and Erg Chigaga dune fields near the towns of Merzouga and Zagora. The golden sand dunes, some reaching 150 meters high, offer a classic desert landscape. Visitors can take camel treks (often at sunset or sunrise), spend nights in traditional Berber camps, ride quad bikes or sandboards, and stargaze under incredibly clear skies. The desert is home to nomadic Berber people who have adapted to the harsh environment. The journey to the Sahara passes through the Atlas Mountains, kasbahs (fortified villages), and ancient caravan routes. The Sahara Desert offers a once-in-a-lifetime adventure and a chance to disconnect from the modern world.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464790719320-516ecd75af6c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Chefchaouen', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Chefchaouen, often called the "Blue City," is a picturesque town nestled in the Rif Mountains of northwestern Morocco. The town is famous for its buildings painted in various shades of blue, a tradition that began with Jewish refugees in the 1930s who believed blue represented heaven. The blue-washed streets create a serene, almost surreal atmosphere that photographers love. Chefchaouen offers a more relaxed, laid-back experience compared to Morocco\'s larger cities. Visitors can explore the medina, hike to the Spanish Mosque for panoramic views, visit the Kasbah Museum, and shop for local handicrafts, including woolen garments and woven blankets. The surrounding mountains offer hiking opportunities, including to the nearby Akchour waterfalls. Chefchaouen\'s unique beauty, relaxed vibe, and mountain setting make it one of Morocco\'s most photogenic destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547489432-cf93fa6c71ee?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Spain (id: 10)
            ['country_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Barcelona', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Barcelona is Spain\'s second-largest city and the capital of Catalonia, known for its unique architecture, vibrant culture, and beautiful Mediterranean beaches. The city is famous for the works of Antoni Gaudí, including the unfinished Sagrada Família basilica, Park Güell, Casa Batlló, and La Pedrera. Barcelona\'s Gothic Quarter (Barri Gòtic) features narrow medieval streets, the Barcelona Cathedral, and remnants of the Roman city. The city hosted the 1992 Olympics, which spurred urban development along the waterfront. La Rambla, a tree-lined pedestrian boulevard, is the city\'s most famous street. Barcelona offers world-class museums, including the Picasso Museum and Joan Miró Foundation. The city\'s food scene ranges from traditional tapas bars to Michelin-starred restaurants. Barcelona\'s combination of history, art, architecture, and beach makes it one of Europe\'s most popular destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1539037116277-4db20889f2d4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Ibiza', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Ibiza is one of Spain\'s Balearic Islands, famous for its vibrant nightlife, beautiful beaches, and bohemian atmosphere. The island is known as a global center for electronic dance music, with world-famous clubs like Pacha, Amnesia, and Ushuaïa hosting top DJs during the summer season. Beyond the nightlife, Ibiza offers beautiful coves and beaches, including Cala Comte, Cala Bassa, and Ses Salines. The island\'s interior features white-washed villages, pine forests, and the UNESCO-listed Old Town (Dalt Vila). Ibiza has a quieter side in the north, known for its yoga retreats, organic farms, and laid-back vibe. The island also has a spiritual history, with Phoenician, Carthaginian, Roman, and Moorish influences. Ibiza\'s combination of party scene, natural beauty, and bohemian culture attracts a diverse crowd of visitors.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519651150555-9d3c3c2c7e0a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Seville', 'trip_type' => 'romantic', 'description' => 'Seville is the capital of Andalusia, known for its passionate flamenco music and dance, delicious tapas, and stunning Moorish architecture. The city\'s most famous landmark is the Real Alcázar, a magnificent palace complex with Mudejar, Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque elements (featured in Game of Thrones). The Seville Cathedral is the largest Gothic cathedral in the world and houses the tomb of Christopher Columbus. The Giralda tower, originally a minaret, offers panoramic views. The Plaza de España, built for the 1929 Ibero-American Exposition, is a masterpiece of regional architecture. Seville is also famous for its spring festivals, including Semana Santa (Holy Week) and Feria de Abril (April Fair). The city\'s narrow streets, orange trees, and warm climate create a romantic atmosphere. Seville\'s rich history, passionate culture, and delicious cuisine make it a highlight of southern Spain.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513442542250-521d6ff5f6bf?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Greece (id: 11)
            ['country_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Santorini', 'trip_type' => 'romantic', 'description' => 'Santorini is a stunning volcanic island in the Aegean Sea, famous for its white-washed buildings with blue domes, spectacular sunsets, and dramatic caldera views. The island was shaped by a massive volcanic eruption around 1600 BCE, which created the caldera and possibly contributed to the decline of the Minoan civilization. The main towns of Fira and Oia cling to the caldera cliffs, offering breathtaking views. Oia is particularly famous for its sunset, drawing crowds each evening. Santorini also features unique volcanic beaches with red, black, and white sand, including Red Beach and Kamari Beach. The ancient site of Akrotiri, preserved by volcanic ash like Pompeii, offers a glimpse into Bronze Age life. Santorini\'s wineries produce distinctive Assyrtiko wines from volcanic soil. The island\'s unique beauty, romantic atmosphere, and stunning views make it one of the world\'s most photographed destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1533105079780-92b9be482077?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Athens', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Athens is one of the world\'s oldest cities, with recorded history spanning over 3,400 years. It is the cradle of Western civilization, birthplace of democracy, philosophy, theater, and the Olympic Games. The city\'s most famous landmark is the Acropolis, an ancient citadel crowned by the Parthenon, dedicated to the goddess Athena. Other ancient sites include the Ancient Agora, Temple of Olympian Zeus, and Theatre of Dionysus. The Acropolis Museum houses artifacts found on the Acropolis. Beyond ancient ruins, Athens is a modern, vibrant city with lively neighborhoods like Plaka (the old town), Monastiraki (known for its flea market), and Psiri (known for nightlife). Greek cuisine, including souvlaki, moussaka, and fresh seafood, is delicious and affordable. Athens combines ancient history with modern energy, making it a fascinating destination for culture lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514041181368-bca62cceffcd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Crete', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Crete is Greece\'s largest island, known for its diverse landscapes, ancient history, and warm hospitality. The island was home to the Minoan civilization, Europe\'s first advanced civilization, with the palace of Knossos near Heraklion. Crete offers stunning natural beauty, including the Samaria Gorge (one of Europe\'s longest gorges), beautiful beaches like Elafonissi (pink sand) and Balos Lagoon, and the palm forest of Vai. The island\'s mountains, including Mount Ida (the birthplace of Zeus in mythology), offer hiking opportunities. Cretan cuisine is considered among the healthiest in the world, featuring olive oil, fresh vegetables, herbs, cheese (especially feta and graviera), and dishes like dakos and kalitsounia. Chania and Rethymno feature beautiful Venetian harbors and old towns. Crete\'s combination of history, nature, and cuisine makes it a complete destination for travelers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531605703851-e1a8cd0c4a48?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // New Zealand (id: 12)
            ['country_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Queenstown', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Queenstown is known as the adventure capital of the world, offering a wide range of adrenaline activities in a stunning setting on the shores of Lake Wakatipu, surrounded by the Southern Alps. The town pioneered commercial bungee jumping with the Kawarau Bridge Bungy. Other activities include skydiving, jet boating on the Shotover River, white-water rafting, paragliding, mountain biking, and zip-lining. In winter, nearby ski fields including Coronet Peak and The Remarkables offer excellent skiing and snowboarding. For those seeking more relaxation, Queenstown offers scenic cruises on the lake, wine tours in the nearby Central Otago region (known for Pinot Noir), and hikes including the Routeburn Track. The Skyline Gondola offers spectacular views. Queenstown\'s combination of adventure, natural beauty, and alpine atmosphere attracts thrill-seekers from around the world.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Rotorua', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Rotorua is New Zealand\'s geothermal wonderland, located in the Taupō Volcanic Zone on the North Island. The city is known for its bubbling mud pools, erupting geysers (including the famous Pohutu Geyser at Te Puia), and hot springs, which create a distinctive sulfur smell. Rotorua is also the heart of Maori culture in New Zealand, with opportunities to experience traditional performances, hangi (earth-cooked meals), and visit living villages like Whakarewarewa. The city offers other attractions including the Redwoods Treewalk through towering California redwoods, the Polynesian Spa (hot springs), and the Agrodome for farm shows. Nearby lakes, including Lake Rotorua and Lake Tarawera, offer fishing, boating, and kayaking. Rotorua\'s unique geothermal activity and rich Maori heritage make it one of New Zealand\'s most distinctive destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516156008625-3a9d6067fab5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Auckland', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Auckland is New Zealand\'s largest city, known as the "City of Sails" for its beautiful harbors and love of sailing. The city is built on a volcanic field, with over 50 volcanic cones, including Maungakiekie / One Tree Hill and Rangitoto Island, a volcanic island accessible by ferry. The Sky Tower, the Southern Hemisphere\'s tallest freestanding structure, offers panoramic views. Auckland\'s waterfront, including the Viaduct Harbour and Wynyard Quarter, features restaurants, bars, and the New Zealand Maritime Museum. The city offers diverse cultural experiences, including the Auckland Art Gallery (the largest art institution in New Zealand), the Auckland War Memorial Museum, and vibrant Pacific Island and Asian communities in neighborhoods like Otara and Dominion Road. The nearby islands of Waiheke (known for vineyards) and Great Barrier offer getaways. Auckland\'s mild climate, beautiful harbors, and diverse culture make it a great starting point for exploring New Zealand.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Egypt (id: 13)
            ['country_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Cairo', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Cairo is the capital of Egypt and the largest city in the Arab world and Africa, known for its ancient history, Islamic architecture, and bustling street life. The city is the gateway to the Pyramids of Giza, the last surviving wonder of the ancient world, located on the outskirts. The Great Sphinx stands guard nearby. The Egyptian Museum in Tahrir Square houses over 120,000 artifacts, including the treasures of Tutankhamun. Islamic Cairo features historic mosques (including the Al-Azhar Mosque and Mosque of Muhammad Ali), madrasas, and the Khan el-Khalili bazaar. Coptic Cairo contains ancient churches, including the Hanging Church, and the Ben Ezra Synagogue. Cairo\'s street food scene offers delicious and cheap options like koshari, falafel, and shawarma. Despite its chaos, Cairo\'s energy, history, and warmth captivate visitors.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503177119275-0aa32b3a9368?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Hurghada', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Hurghada is a resort city on Egypt\'s Red Sea coast, known for its beautiful beaches, clear waters, and world-class diving and snorkeling. The Red Sea is famous for its vibrant coral reefs and abundant marine life, including colorful fish, dolphins, turtles, and sharks. Giftun Island National Park is a popular day trip for snorkeling. Hurghada offers a range of water sports, including windsurfing, kitesurfing, and parasailing. The city is divided into three main areas: El Dahar (the old town), Sekalla (the central area), and El Mamsha (the modern resort strip). Hurghada offers many all-inclusive resorts, making it a convenient and affordable beach destination. The city also serves as a base for trips to Luxor and other ancient sites. Hurghada\'s combination of Red Sea beauty and resort amenities attracts beach lovers, divers, and families.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1562693266-5a3b8ab84114?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Luxor', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Luxor is often called the world\'s greatest open-air museum, located on the site of the ancient city of Thebes, the capital of Egypt during the New Kingdom. The city is divided by the Nile River: the East Bank, known as the city of the living, features the magnificent Karnak Temple (the largest religious complex ever built) and Luxor Temple, connected by the Avenue of Sphinxes. The West Bank, known as the city of the dead, features the Valley of the Kings (where pharaohs including Tutankhamun were buried), the Valley of the Queens, the Temple of Hatshepsut (Egypt\'s only female pharaoh), and the Colossi of Memnon. Visitors can explore these sites by foot, taxi, or horse-drawn carriage. Hot air balloon rides over the West Bank at sunrise offer spectacular views. Luxor\'s incredible concentration of ancient Egyptian monuments makes it an essential destination for history lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1564257631407-4deb1f99d992?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Mexico (id: 14)
            ['country_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Cancun', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Cancun is a world-famous resort city on Mexico\'s Yucatán Peninsula, known for its stunning Caribbean beaches, turquoise waters, and vibrant nightlife. The city is divided into two main areas: El Centro (the downtown area) and the Zona Hotelera (Hotel Zone), a 22-kilometer L-shaped strip of beachfront resorts, restaurants, and nightclubs. Cancun offers beautiful white-sand beaches, water sports including snorkeling, diving, jet skiing, and parasailing. The city is a gateway to the Riviera Maya, with day trips to the Mayan ruins of Chichen Itza (one of the New Seven Wonders of the World), Tulum, and Coba, as well as the island of Isla Mujeres. Cancun\'s underwater museum (MUSA) features over 500 life-sized sculptures. The city hosts a vibrant spring break scene but also offers quieter resorts and family-friendly options. Cancun\'s combination of beach beauty, Mayan history, and modern amenities makes it one of Mexico\'s top destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512813195386-60cf811b74a2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Mexico City', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Mexico City is one of the world\'s largest and most vibrant cities, built on the site of the Aztec capital Tenochtitlan. The city\'s historic center, the Zócalo, is one of the world\'s largest squares, surrounded by the Metropolitan Cathedral, National Palace (with Diego Rivera murals), and Templo Mayor (Aztec ruins). The city offers world-class museums, including the National Museum of Anthropology (the best collection of pre-Columbian art) and the Frida Kahlo Museum (the Blue House). The neighborhoods of Coyoacán (with its cobblestone streets), Roma, and Condesa offer beautiful architecture, cafes, and restaurants. Mexico City is a culinary capital, with everything from street tacos and tamales to fine dining (including several of the world\'s best restaurants). The city\'s cultural richness, energy, and hospitality make it one of the world\'s most exciting urban destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512813195386-60cf811b74a2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Chichen Itza', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Chichen Itza is the most famous Mayan archaeological site, located in Mexico\'s Yucatán Peninsula. It was designated one of the New Seven Wonders of the World in 2007 and is a UNESCO World Heritage site. The site\'s most iconic structure is El Castillo (the Temple of Kukulcán), a pyramid with 365 steps (one for each day of the year). During the spring and autumn equinoxes, the sun creates a serpent shadow descending the pyramid. Other structures include the Great Ball Court (the largest in Mesoamerica), the Temple of Warriors (with hundreds of columns), the Group of a Thousand Columns, and the Sacred Cenote (a natural sinkhole used for sacrifices). The site also features a cenote (natural swimming hole) where visitors can cool off. Chichen Itza offers a fascinating glimpse into Mayan astronomy, architecture, and culture, making it a must-see for visitors to Mexico.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Germany (id: 15)
            ['country_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Berlin', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Berlin is Germany\'s capital and largest city, known for its complex history, vibrant art scene, and creative energy. The city is famous for remnants of the Berlin Wall, including the East Side Gallery (a 1.3-kilometer stretch covered in murals). The Brandenburg Gate is the city\'s most famous landmark. Museum Island, a UNESCO World Heritage site, features five world-class museums. The city\'s history is explored at the Topography of Terror (documenting Nazi crimes), the Holocaust Memorial, and the Jewish Museum. Berlin also offers the Reichstag Building (German parliament) with its glass dome, Checkpoint Charlie (former Cold War border crossing), and the Berlin Cathedral. Beyond history, Berlin is known for its nightlife, with clubs like Berghain legendary among electronic music fans. The city\'s neighborhoods, including Kreuzberg, Friedrichshain, and Prenzlauer Berg, offer street art, cafes, and alternative culture. Berlin\'s gritty authenticity, cultural richness, and youthful energy make it one of Europe\'s most dynamic cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1467269204594-9661b134dd2b?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Munich', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Munich is the capital of Bavaria, known for its beer gardens, Oktoberfest, and Bavarian culture. The city\'s most famous event is Oktoberfest, the world\'s largest Volksfest (beer festival and traveling funfair), attracting over 6 million visitors annually. The city offers beautiful architecture, including the Neues Rathaus (New Town Hall) with its famous Glockenspiel in Marienplatz, the Frauenkirche (Cathedral of Our Dear Lady), and the Residenz (former royal palace). Munich is a gateway to outdoor adventures in the Bavarian Alps, including hiking, skiing, and visits to Neuschwanstein Castle (the fairy-tale castle that inspired Disney). The English Garden (Englischer Garten) is one of the world\'s largest urban parks, larger than New York\'s Central Park. The city is also home to the Deutsches Museum (world\'s largest science and technology museum) and the BMW Museum. Munich\'s combination of culture, beer, and proximity to the Alps makes it a favorite among travelers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1508050919630-b135583b29f4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Black Forest', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'The Black Forest (Schwarzwald) is a mountainous region in southwestern Germany, known for its dense forests, picturesque villages, hiking trails, and cuckoo clocks. The region is famous for its natural beauty, including lakes (particularly Lake Titisee and Lake Schluchsee), waterfalls (including Triberg Falls, Germany\'s highest), and scenic drives (including the Schwarzwaldhochstraße or Black Forest High Road). The region is associated with the Brothers Grimm fairy tales, including Hansel and Gretel and Snow White. Visitors can explore charming towns like Freiburg (with its cathedral and university), Baden-Baden (famous for its thermal baths), and Triberg (home to cuckoo clock shops). The region is also known for its Black Forest cake (Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte), ham, and cherry schnapps. Hiking and biking trails crisscross the region, and in winter, there are opportunities for skiing and snowshoeing. The Black Forest\'s combination of natural beauty, traditional culture, and outdoor activities makes it a popular destination for nature lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506182982230-38fdefcef3a8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // South Africa (id: 16)
            ['country_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Cape Town', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Cape Town is one of Africa\'s most beautiful cities, nestled between Table Mountain and the Atlantic Ocean. The city is known for its stunning natural setting, with Table Mountain National Park offering hiking, cable car rides, and panoramic views. Robben Island, where Nelson Mandela was imprisoned for 18 years, is a UNESCO World Heritage site and a powerful symbol of South Africa\'s struggle for freedom. The Victoria & Alfred Waterfront offers shopping, dining, and entertainment. The Cape of Good Hope, the southwestern tip of Africa, offers dramatic scenery and wildlife, including baboons and ostriches. Boulders Beach is home to a colony of African penguins. The city\'s diverse neighborhoods, including Bo-Kaap (with its colorful houses), offer cultural experiences. Cape Town is also a gateway to the Cape Winelands, including Stellenbosch and Franschhoek. The city\'s combination of natural beauty, history, and outdoor activities makes it a top African destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Kruger National Park', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Kruger National Park is one of Africa\'s largest and most famous game reserves, covering nearly 20,000 square kilometers in northeastern South Africa. The park is home to the Big Five (lion, leopard, elephant, rhino, and buffalo), as well as cheetahs, wild dogs, giraffes, zebras, hippos, crocodiles, and over 500 bird species. Visitors can explore the park through self-drive safaris, guided game drives, or walking safaris. The park offers a range of accommodation, from basic rest camps to luxury private lodges. The best time for wildlife viewing is during the dry winter months (May to September), when animals gather around water sources. The park is part of the Great Limpopo Transfrontier Park, which links Kruger with parks in Mozambique and Zimbabwe. Kruger offers an accessible and affordable safari experience, making it one of Africa\'s most popular wildlife destinations. The park\'s incredible biodiversity and conservation success make it a must-visit for nature lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Johannesburg', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Johannesburg, often called Joburg or Jozi, is South Africa\'s largest city and economic heart. The city is known for its vibrant energy, cultural diversity, and complex history. The Apartheid Museum offers a powerful and comprehensive look at South Africa\'s apartheid era, essential for understanding the country\'s journey to democracy. Soweto, the famous township, offers tours including visits to the Mandela House (Nelson Mandela\'s former home) and the Hector Pieterson Memorial (dedicated to a child killed during the 1976 Soweto Uprising). The city\'s arts and culture scene thrives in neighborhoods like Maboneng (known for street art, galleries, and markets) and Braamfontein. The Cradle of Humankind, a UNESCO World Heritage site just outside the city, features fossil sites of early hominids. Johannesburg\'s energy, resilience, and cultural richness offer a uniquely South African urban experience.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // United Kingdom (id: 17)
            ['country_id' => 17, 'name' => 'London', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'London is the capital of the United Kingdom and one of the world\'s most visited cities, known for its history, culture, and diversity. The city\'s iconic landmarks include Big Ben (the nickname for the Great Bell of the clock at the Houses of Parliament), the London Eye, Tower of London, Tower Bridge, Buckingham Palace (the monarch\'s official residence), and Trafalgar Square. The British Museum houses the Rosetta Stone, Egyptian mummies, and the Elgin Marbles. Other world-class museums include the Natural History Museum, Victoria and Albert Museum, and Tate Modern. London\'s West End is famous for theater, with musicals and plays drawing crowds nightly. The city\'s neighborhoods, from Notting Hill (known for its colorful houses and carnival) to Camden (known for its markets and alternative culture), offer diverse experiences. London\'s parks, including Hyde Park and Regent\'s Park, offer green space. The city\'s food scene reflects its diversity, from traditional fish and chips to Michelin-starred restaurants. London\'s energy, history, and cultural richness make it one of the world\'s great cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 17, 'name' => 'Edinburgh', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Edinburgh is the capital of Scotland, known for its dramatic castle perched on an extinct volcano, medieval Old Town, and elegant Georgian New Town (both UNESCO World Heritage sites). The Edinburgh Castle dominates the skyline and houses the Crown Jewels of Scotland and the Stone of Destiny. The Royal Mile, the castle\'s main artery, features historic buildings, shops, pubs, and St. Giles\' Cathedral. The city is famous for its festivals, particularly the Edinburgh Festival Fringe (the world\'s largest arts festival) in August, as well as the Edinburgh International Festival, Military Tattoo, and Hogmanay (New Year\'s Eve) celebration. Arthur\'s Seat, an ancient volcano in Holyrood Park, offers hiking and panoramic views. The city\'s literary heritage includes authors like Sir Walter Scott, Robert Louis Stevenson, and J.K. Rowling (who wrote much of Harry Potter in Edinburgh cafes). Edinburgh\'s combination of history, culture, and natural beauty makes it one of Europe\'s most beautiful cities.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 17, 'name' => 'Lake District', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'The Lake District is a mountainous region in northwest England, known for its stunning lakes, forests, and mountains (or "fells"). It is England\'s largest National Park and a UNESCO World Heritage site. The region is famous for its natural beauty, which inspired the Lake Poets, including William Wordsworth, Samuel Taylor Coleridge, and Robert Southey. The most popular lakes include Windermere (the largest), Derwentwater, Ullswater, and Coniston Water. Scafell Pike, England\'s highest mountain, offers challenging hiking. Other popular peaks include Helvellyn and Catbells. The region offers hiking, boating, cycling, and fishing. Charming towns and villages include Ambleside, Bowness-on-Windermere, Keswick, and Grasmere (home to Wordsworth\'s Dove Cottage). The Lake District\'s combination of natural beauty, literary heritage, and outdoor activities makes it one of England\'s most popular destinations for nature lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Turkey (id: 18)
            ['country_id' => 18, 'name' => 'Istanbul', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Istanbul is the only city in the world spanning two continents (Europe and Asia), divided by the Bosphorus Strait. The city was the capital of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empires, and its rich history is evident in its architecture. The Hagia Sophia, a masterpiece of Byzantine architecture, has served as a cathedral, mosque, and now museum. The Blue Mosque (Sultan Ahmed Mosque) features six minarets and stunning blue Iznik tiles. Topkapi Palace was the Ottoman sultans\' home for 400 years. The Grand Bazaar, one of the world\'s oldest and largest covered markets, features over 4,000 shops. The Basilica Cistern, an underground water storage, offers a mysterious atmosphere. The city\'s food scene includes kebabs, mezes, baklava, and Turkish delight. A Bosphorus cruise offers views of palaces, mosques, and bridges. Istanbul\'s energy, history, and unique position between East and West make it a fascinating destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 18, 'name' => 'Cappadocia', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Cappadocia is a historical region in central Turkey, famous for its unique "fairy chimney" rock formations, cave dwellings, and underground cities. The region was formed by volcanic eruptions followed by erosion, creating a surreal landscape. Hot air balloon rides at sunrise are the most popular activity, offering spectacular views of the valleys and rock formations. Visitors can explore the Göreme Open Air Museum, a UNESCO World Heritage site with rock-cut churches and frescoes. Underground cities, including Derinkuyu and Kaymaklı, were used by early Christians as hiding places. Other activities include hiking through valleys (such as Love Valley, Pigeon Valley, and Rose Valley), staying in cave hotels, and attending pottery workshops in Avanos. Cappadocia\'s otherworldly landscape and unique history make it one of Turkey\'s most magical destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 18, 'name' => 'Pamukkale', 'trip_type' => 'nature', 'description' => 'Pamukkale, meaning "cotton castle" in Turkish, is a natural site famous for its white travertine terraces formed by calcium-rich hot springs. The terraces cascade down the hillside, creating pools of turquoise water. Visitors can walk on the terraces (barefoot) and bathe in the thermal waters. Above the terraces lies the ancient city of Hierapolis, a Greco-Roman city founded in the 2nd century BCE. Highlights include the well-preserved theater, the Necropolis (one of the largest ancient cemeteries in Turkey), the Temple of Apollo, and the Antique Pool (where Cleopatra supposedly swam). The combination of natural beauty and ancient history makes Pamukkale a UNESCO World Heritage site. The site is particularly beautiful at sunset when the terraces glow. Pamukkale offers a unique experience of bathing in history while enjoying stunning natural scenery.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Indonesia (id: 19)
            ['country_id' => 19, 'name' => 'Bali', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'Bali is Indonesia\'s most famous island, known as the "Island of the Gods" for its beautiful beaches, lush rice terraces, volcanic mountains, and thousands of temples. The island offers a diverse range of experiences: surf beaches (Kuta, Canggu, Uluwatu), family-friendly beaches (Sanur, Nusa Dua), and quiet beaches (Amed, Lovina). The cultural heart is Ubud, known for its monkey forest, rice terraces (Tegalalang), yoga studios, and traditional dance performances. The island\'s temples include Tanah Lot (perched on a rock formation), Uluwatu (on a cliff edge), and Besakih (the "mother temple"). Mount Batur offers sunrise trekking. Bali is also known for its spas, wellness retreats, and cuisine (including nasi goreng, satay, and babi guling). The island\'s combination of natural beauty, culture, and hospitality makes it one of the world\'s most popular destinations.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 19, 'name' => 'Jakarta', 'trip_type' => 'adventure', 'description' => 'Jakarta is Indonesia\'s capital and largest city, a bustling metropolis with a rich history and vibrant energy. The city\'s Old Town (Kota Tua) features Dutch colonial buildings, including the Jakarta History Museum (former city hall) and Wayang Museum (puppet museum). The National Monument (Monas) symbolizes Indonesian independence. The Istiqlal Mosque is Southeast Asia\'s largest mosque, located across from the Jakarta Cathedral. Jakarta offers world-class shopping at malls like Grand Indonesia and Plaza Indonesia, as well as traditional markets. The city\'s food scene includes street food (nasi goreng, sate, gado-gado) and fine dining. The Thousand Islands (Kepulauan Seribu), a chain of islands north of Jakarta, offer beach and diving escapes from the city. Jakarta\'s energy, diversity, and cultural landmarks make it an exciting, if challenging, urban destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 19, 'name' => 'Yogyakarta', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Yogyakarta (often called Jogja) is the cultural heart of Java, known for its traditional arts, ancient temples, and royal heritage. The city is home to two UNESCO World Heritage sites: Borobudur, the world\'s largest Buddhist temple (built in the 9th century), and Prambanan, a stunning Hindu temple complex dedicated to the Trimurti (Brahma, Vishnu, Shiva). The city itself features the Kraton (sultan\'s palace), the Taman Sari (water castle), and the bustling Malioboro street market. Yogyakarta is a center for traditional arts, including batik (textile art), wayang kulit (shadow puppetry), and gamelan music. The city also offers the Merapi volcano (one of Indonesia\'s most active) for hiking or jeep tours. Yogyakarta\'s combination of ancient temples, royal heritage, and living traditions makes it a must-visit for culture lovers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Portugal (id: 20)
            ['country_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Lisbon', 'trip_type' => 'culture', 'description' => 'Lisbon is Portugal\'s hilly coastal capital, known for its pastel-colored buildings, historic trams, and Fado music. The city\'s historic neighborhoods include Alfama (the oldest, with narrow streets and the São Jorge Castle), Bairro Alto (known for nightlife and Fado houses), and Belém (known for the Belém Tower, Jerónimos Monastery, and Pasteis de Belém custard tarts). The city\'s trams, particularly Tram 28, offer a scenic tour of the city\'s hills. The Lisbon Oceanarium is one of the world\'s largest aquariums. The city offers beautiful views from its many miradouros (viewpoints), including Miradouro da Senhora do Monte and Miradouro de Santa Luzia. Lisbon is also known for its food scene, including fresh seafood, grilled sardines, and ginjinha (cherry liqueur). The city\'s combination of history, culture, and warm hospitality makes it one of Europe\'s most charming capitals.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Algarve', 'trip_type' => 'beach', 'description' => 'The Algarve is Portugal\'s southernmost region, famous for its golden beaches, dramatic sea caves, and year-round sunshine. The region offers over 150 kilometers of coastline, with popular resorts including Albufeira, Lagos, Portimão, and Vilamoura. The most famous natural attractions include the Benagil Sea Cave (accessible by boat or kayak), Ponta da Piedade (a headland with stunning rock formations), and the Ria Formosa Natural Park (a lagoon system with barrier islands). The Algarve offers a range of beaches, from long sandy stretches to hidden coves surrounded by cliffs. The region is also known for its golf courses (over 30), water sports (surfing, diving, sailing), and seafood (especially cataplana, a seafood stew). The Algarve\'s mild climate (over 300 days of sunshine annually), beautiful beaches, and relaxed atmosphere make it Portugal\'s premier beach destination.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['country_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Porto', 'trip_type' => 'romantic', 'description' => 'Porto is Portugal\'s second-largest city, known for its port wine, stunning bridges, and romantic riverside charm. The city\'s historic center, Ribeira, is a UNESCO World Heritage site with narrow streets, colorful houses, and restaurants along the Douro River. The Dom Luís I Bridge, designed by a student of Gustave Eiffel, connects Porto with Vila Nova de Gaia, where the port wine cellars are located. Visitors can tour the cellars (including Taylor\'s, Graham\'s, and Sandeman) and taste port wine. The city\'s landmarks include the Clérigos Tower (offering panoramic views), the Livraria Lello (one of the world\'s most beautiful bookstores, which inspired J.K. Rowling), and the São Bento Railway Station (famous for its azulejo tile panels). The Douro River offers scenic cruises, including trips through the Douro Valley wine region. Porto\'s romantic atmosphere, port wine heritage, and riverside beauty make it a favorite among travelers.', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
